			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Shuriken of Eternity, worth it?<a name="49552"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 1 04 2:47 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>A few things about pulling with thrown objects...
<br />

<br />
The mechanics of using a throwing object are a bit different than using songs or bellow. First off that delay number is only one of two main limitations to determining when you can throw your next shuriken. The second limitation is your first throw must complete its path. That doesnt seem like much, but it takes some getting used to as it ends up being somewhere inbetween the instant agro ability of bellow and the casting time of songs. Even if I am pulling an AE group from a healthy distance away, by the time my second shuriken leaves my hand, I likely have the mobs pulled from the first shuriken in my face. There are few places I can pull an AE crowd with more than one shuriken. Compared to using HoS, retargetting during the song, and hitting bellow - shurikens will seem like waiting forever so the real advantages for shurikens would only come in if you really do have enough time to get 3 shurikens off before your retreat or if you are doing double pulls less than 18 secodns apart from each other (which you very well may be doing if you are used to pulling mobs up, fading, and having additional pullers bring those mobs off to wherever they eventually are going.) Offhand the only place I can thing of using more than 2 shurikens at a time is at the Cori event when I go to the far end of the wall and swim back towards the raid constantly retargetting and flinging shurikens as I swim along the top of the wall towards the raid. It works, but its a pretty special case.
<br />

<br />
Also LoS is kinda odd for thrown objects. You need it to initiate a throw but it is not needed for it to land. This is similar to using songs to pull but sometimes it works in the opposite way. For a song - you can start moving away (and out of LoS) once it starts up and get the actual agro without LoS. for a thrown object, often while throwing at a pathing mob you will see the shuriken bend its path to catch up to the target - even if it goes around a corner and out of your LoS. On the surface this is the same thing, but it does cause one problem with thrown objects - depending on how the shuriken redirects its path it may hit a wall or a stationary object or possibly worst of all another mob than your target. In all of these cases it will not directly agro your target. If it hit another mob it will directly agro that mob and be primary agro on you and your actual target may or may not assist and gain secondary agro.
<br />

<br />
To touch on another point a little more, if the shuriken contacts any geometry before reaching your target, it will not agro anything at all - no matter how close it was to your target at the time. If it contacts your target it will always agro the target but may still be a &quot;miss&quot; as far as determining damage. hitting geometery has nothing to do with any skills in game - or really even luck - you can 100% avoid it if you are aware of your LoS. Therefore throwing skill takes no relevance at all in the ability to use shurikens to pull. prior to DX9 walled mobs were a pain to pull cause for some reason the shuriken would be registered as hitting the wall before your target - just like rangers not able to use archery for range damage on walled mobs.
<br />

<br />
The last major limitation to using shurikens is elevation difference. songs and bellow are not limited by a Z-axis, but throwing is. You may very easily see your target - be will within range of it - and have a perfect LoS, but if the Z-axis difference is too great you cannot throw the shuriken. Songs and bellow have this point of difference heavily in their favor. One more limitation, but minor, is you cannot use a ranged weapon if too close to your target. If you are that close, however, you can always slap the mob with the back of your hand to get its attention.
<br />

<br />
Stats on Time shuikens are great and easily worth permanently bagging range items like a marsingers Gem or Secrets of the Planes. However there are still even better pure range items at that stage of the game as well. MY opinion on non-monks getting or not getting time shurikens is admittedly slightly biased, but for some logical reasons. The pouch is still rare and likely will take many Time clearings before your guild has more than one of them. It is a gigantic upgrade for a monk to have in terms of ranged damage. It actually counts for substantial DPS in ranged fights. Prior to Phase 5 of time there is not one single item in game that a monk can obtain that will provide them with even 10 DPS capability in range damage. I am aware of PoHate shurikens (I have a stack of them myself) but the fact that it is impossible to keep a supply of them at hand for a ranged battle pretty much rules them out of consideration as an alternative. Not needing to swap range items is a nice plus for monks with time shurikens and a throwing range of 250 is handy as well, but the ability to actually be useful in ranged fights is the REAL big reason this item is sought after by monks so much. A guild benefits the most overall as a guild if the monks get the pouches first - even if monks are not used as pullers.
<br />

<br />
Of course monks in raiding guilds is becoming harder and harder to find and it is better to have the pouch in an active members hand than an alt or inactive monk. If all your active monks all have pouches, there really is no shame in requesting one before an alt monk twink gets one instead.
<br />

<br />
--Senador</span></td>
